Stealing credit card information from a public database is done by someone who has access to the database, either through breaking into the system or having been given permission. Once access is granted, the thief can run scripts or programs that search for patterns in the data and grab numbers along with other account details such as names and expiration dates. 

The greatest risks associated with stealing credit card numbers from a public database include identity theft, financial ruin for those affected and reputation damage for companies whose databases have been breached. It can also open up individuals to fraudulent activities such as taking out loans in their name or making large purchases using their information.  Companies may incur costs related to recovering lost or stolen data, notifying customers whose information was obtained and providing them with identity protection services.
